                  </persName>
            . I am wife to 
               <persName id="t18150913-17-person224">
                  John 
                  Clare
               <interp inst="t18150913-17-person224" type="surname" value="Clare"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150913-17-person224" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150913-17-person224" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and my husband's house is in Type-street. On the 24th of June, I let one room on the first floor to the prisoner at the bar, and let with it all the furniture necessary for a bed and amongst other things, three blankets; he paid no rent, and left the lodging on the Saturday. I went into the room on the Monday morning, and the blanket was gone.</p>
               <p>GEORGE GARRAND. I am shopman to Mr. Timbleby,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181509130011"></xptr>a pawnbroker, at No. 8, Old street-road, This blanket was pawned by a man in regimentals, whom I believe to be the prisoner, on the 6th of July, and I advanced two shillings and sixpence upon it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150913-17-person225">
                  JAMES 
                  BINN
               <interp inst="t18150913-17-person225" type="surname" value="BINN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150913-17-person225" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18150913-17-person225" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I apprehended the prisoner at another lodging. He gave me the duplicate of a blanket, which he acknowledged he had stolen, and said, it was out of distress.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18150913-17-person226">
